==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|la|en}} ''[[depretiare]]'', ''[[depreciare]]'', to depreciate, from ''[[de-#Latin|de-]]'' + ''[[pretium]]'', price

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/dɪˈpɹiːʃɪeɪt/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|depreciat|ing}}

# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To lessen in price or estimated value; to lower the worth of; to represent as of little value or claim to esteem; to undervalue.
#* Cudworth
#*: {{...}} which {{...}} some over-severe philosophers may look upon fastidiously, or undervalue and '''depreciate'''.
#* Burke
#*: To prove that the Americans ought not to be free, we are obliged to '''depreciate''' the value of freedom itself.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To reduce in value over time.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[belittle]].

====Synonyms====
* (''reduce in value over time''):
* (''belittle''): [[do down]]

====Antonyms====
* (''reduce in value over time''): [[appreciate]]
* (''belittle''): [[aggrandise]]/[[aggrandize]], [[big up]] {{qualifier|slang}}

